), the Green's function would be 
\begin_inset Formula $c\ln|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|$
\end_inset

 from the previous problem, for some 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 that you found; for simplicity, in this problem just suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1$
\end_inset

.
 With the circle there, the solution is changedâ€”it not only has the 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|$
\end_inset

 term coming directly from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(\vec{x}-\vec{x}')$
\end_inset

, but there are also terms coming from the cylinderâ€”compared to the empty-space
 solution, there are additional source terms on 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Omega$
\end_inset

 so that the total 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 satisfies the boundary condition.
 The (first-kind) integral-equation formulation of this (as discussed in
 class in 3d) is to put 
\emph on
unknown
\emph default
 sources with density 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(x)$
\end_inset

 all around 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Omega$
\end_inset

, so that the total solution: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=\ln|\vec{x}-\vec{x}'|+\int_{d\Omega}\sigma(\vec{x}'')\ln|\vec{x}-\vec{x}''|d\vec{x}''\]

\end_inset

satisfies the boundary condition 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\vec{x},\vec{x}')=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\in d\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 We then try to find 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\vec{x}'')$
\end_inset

, discretized/approximated in some way, to make this happen.
 (In the electrostatic interpretation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 is an induced charge density on the cylinder surface.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, we will approximate the continuous distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\vec{x}'')$
\end_inset

